6000|$|After he {{has learned}} all these matters the amateur has still {{a great deal to}} acquire. He may now know a real <b>Elzevir</b> from a book which is not an <b>Elzevir</b> at all. But there are {{enormous}} differences of value, rarity, and excellence among the productions of the Elzevirian press. The bookstalls teem with small, [...] "cropped," [...] dingy, dirty, battered Elzevirian editions of the classics, NOT [...] "of the good date." [...] On these it is not worth while to expend a couple of shillings, especially as Elzevirian type is too small to be read with comfort by most modern eyes. No, let the collector save his money; avoid littering his shelves with what he will soon find to be rubbish, and let him wait the chance of acquiring a really beautiful and rare <b>Elzevir.</b>|$|E
6000|$|Nay, here 'midst Rhodian roses, 'Midst {{tissues of}} Cashmere, The Soul sublime reposes, And knows not hope nor fear; Here all {{she sees her}} own is, And musical her moan is, O'er Caxtons and Bodonis, Aldine and <b>Elzevir!</b> ...|$|E
